### Converted Endpoint

```javascript
// GET /api/posts?limit=20&after=<cursor>
async function getPosts(req, res) {
    // --- Parse & validate inputs ---
    const limit = Math.min(parseInt(req.query.limit) || 20, 100); // cap at 100
    const afterCursor = req.query.after;

    let cursorData = null;
    if (afterCursor !== undefined) {
        cursorData = decodeCursor(afterCursor);
        if (!cursorData) {
            return res.status(400).json({
                error: 'Invalid cursor. The `after` parameter is malformed or expired.',
            });
        }
    }

    // --- Build query (no OFFSET, no COUNT) ---
    let query;
    let params;

    if (cursorData) {
        // Compound cursor condition for (created_at DESC, id DESC) ordering.
        //
        // "After the cursor" means: rows that would sort later in the result set,
        // i.e., have a strictly earlier created_at, OR the same created_at but a
        // lower id (both columns are DESC).
        //
        //   (created_at < $1) OR (created_at = $1 AND id < $2)
        //
        // This is equivalent to the SQL row-value expression:
        //   (created_at, id) < ($1::timestamptz, $2)
        query = `
            SELECT id, title, content, author_id, created_at
            FROM posts
            WHERE published = true
              AND (
                    created_at < $1
                    OR (created_at = $1 AND id < $2)
                  )
            ORDER BY created_at DESC, id DESC
            LIMIT $3
        `;
        params = [cursorData.created_at, cursorData.id, limit + 1];
    } else {
        // No cursor provided → first page, no cursor filter needed.
        query = `
            SELECT id, title, content, author_id, created_at
            FROM posts
            WHERE published = true
            ORDER BY created_at DESC, id DESC
            LIMIT $1
        `;
        params = [limit + 1];
    }

    // --- Execute and apply N+1 trick ---
    const result = await db.query(query, params);
    const rows = result.rows;

    // If we got limit+1 rows back, there IS a next page.
    const hasMore = rows.length > limit;

    // Only return `limit` rows to the client; the extra row was just a probe.
    const posts = hasMore ? rows.slice(0, limit) : rows;

    // Build the next cursor from the LAST row we're actually returning,
    // not the probe row — this is where the next page should start after.
    const nextCursor = hasMore ? encodeCursor(posts[posts.length - 1]) : null;

    return res.json({
        posts,
        pagination: {
            hasMore,
            nextCursor,   // null when on the last page
            limit,
        },
    });
}
```

---

### How to Paginate (Client Usage)

```
GET /api/posts?limit=20                          → first page
GET /api/posts?limit=20&after=<nextCursor>       → second page
GET /api/posts?limit=20&after=<nextCursor>       → third page, etc.
// Stop when pagination.hasMore === false (nextCursor will be null)
```

---

## Why Cursor Pagination Is Superior Here

| Problem | Offset | Cursor |
|---|---|---|
| **Skipped / duplicated rows** | Rows inserted between pages shift the offset window, causing items to appear on two pages or vanish entirely. | The `WHERE (created_at, id) < (x, y)` anchor is stable — inserts elsewhere don't affect it. |
| **Performance on large tables** | `OFFSET 10000` forces PostgreSQL to scan and discard 10,000 rows before returning anything. Cost grows linearly with page depth. | The cursor filters directly via an index seek; cost is constant regardless of how deep in the dataset you are. |
| **Expensive `COUNT(*)` query** | Required to calculate `totalPages`, and it's a full table scan on large datasets. | Eliminated entirely — the N+1 trick tells you whether a next page exists at zero extra cost. |
| **Correct ordering guarantee** | Page 3 may overlap with page 2 if rows were inserted while the user was reading. | Compound `(created_at, id)` cursor is unique (assuming unique IDs) and deterministic, so ordering is stable even under concurrent writes. |

The compound cursor on `(created_at, id)` is necessary because `created_at` alone is not unique — two posts created in the same millisecond would produce an ambiguous cursor. Adding `id` as a tiebreaker makes every cursor point to exactly one row.

